  <glossdiv>
	<title>J</title>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm >connection-file</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A file containing xml-description of a network's connections between edges.</para>
		<para>Optional input to sumo-netconvert. Is meant to be used in conjunction with an edge- and a node-file.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
  </glossdiv>


  <glossdiv>
	<title>D</title>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm >detector</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>Part of a network: An artificial device for object states recognition and/or logging.</para>
		<para>See: induction loop</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm >detector measures</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>File: A file generated by the virtual induction loops.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm >district</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A logical artifact, joining streets or describing an area of the network.</para>
		<para>Optional element of a SUMO-network. Needed with the od2trips-application to map district-based od-matrix - data onto the network's streets.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
  </glossdiv>

  <glossdiv>
	<title>E</title>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm >edge</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>An edge is a single-directed street connection between two points (nodes). An edge may contain sections (logitudal segments) and lanes (orthogonal segments).</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm >edge-file</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A file containing xml-description of a network's edges.</para>
		<para>Optional input to sumo-netconvert. Is meant to be used in conjunction with a node-file.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm >emitter</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>See source.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
  </glossdiv>

  <glossdiv>
	<title>I</title>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm >induction loop</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A detector placed on a certain position on a certain lane which recognizes vehicles passing it and logs their values (speed, size etc.)</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
  </glossdiv>

  <glossdiv>
	<title>J</title>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>junction</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>In general, a junction is a node. We use the word junction mostly for nodes that connect real streets in contrast to nodes which may also be points which are used as geometrical ending points of segments, where no real junction can be found.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>junction logic</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A logical part of a junction that determines the right-of-way of the vehicles that are currently in the area of this junction.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
  </glossdiv>

  <glossdiv>
	<title>L</title>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm >lane</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A lane is a part of an edge. An edge may consist of several parallel lanes.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm >link</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A connection between two lanes within a junction. Witin the microsim, each Lane has links (connections) to other lanes. As an additional parameter the information whether approaching vehicles which want to use this link shall yield.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm >logic</glossterm>
	  <glosssee>junction logic</glosssee>
	</glossentry>
  </glossdiv>

  <glossdiv>
	<title>M</title>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>macroscopic</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>In a macroscopic traffic simulation, the atomic instances are roads (see microscopic and submicroscopic)</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>microscopic</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>In a microcopic traffic simulation, the atomic instances (the instances which are simulated) are vehicles. SUMO also regards single persons as atomic instances. Compare to macroscopic and submicroscopic.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>multimodal</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>Means that the simulation is able to process different types of traffic like car driving, busses and railways.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
  </glossdiv>

  <glossdiv>
	<title>N</title>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm >(street) network</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>In our terms, a network is the combination of streets (edges/lanes) and junctions (nodes) that build up the topology of the streets.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>network description</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>Data that contain information about streets (edges/lanes) and junctions together with their attributes, so that a network is described.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>network state</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>File: A description of the situation within the network including all driving vehicles together with the information on which lane and which position each vehicle is and what its speed is.</para>
		<para>SUMO is generating such a description using the -o - parameter.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>network workload</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>File: A description of the networks workload, containing the aggregated utilisation over a time to specify.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>No Junction</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A connection between streets where no interference between the incoming roads takes place.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>node</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A node is a single point anywhere in the world given by it's cartesian x- and y- position. Nodes may be connected by edges or sections. See also junction.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm >node-file</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A file containing xml-description of a network's nodes.</para>
		<para>Optional input to sumo-netconvert. Is meant to be used in conjunction with an edge-file.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
  </glossdiv>

  <glossdiv>
	<title>O</title>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>od-matrix</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>An origin-destination matrix containing descriptions of routes specified by their occurence number (within a certain time) given the point they start (origin) and the point they end at (destination) as table cell indices.</para>
		<para>Different time scales may be used for such matrices and the definition of a day's trips (on a certain network) may be described using several matrices.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>option</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>An option is a variable that may be changed by the user when starting the program by supportting command line parameter or a configuration file.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
  </glossdiv>

  <glossdiv>
	<title>P</title>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>priority</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>Streets may differ in their priorities - a highway for instance has always a higher priority than an off-road. By now, we are using an internal classification for roads (see [1])</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>Priority Junction</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A junction where the movement of vehicles is determined by their different priorities.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
  </glossdiv>

  <glossdiv>
	<title>R</title>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>Right-Before-Left Junction</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A junction where traffic coming from the right side has always a higher priority than the current.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>Route</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A route is a description of a vehicle's movement within the network holding all edges the vehicles passes.</para>
		<para>The difference to a trip definition is that all edges are explicitely given.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
  </glossdiv>

  <glossdiv>
	<title>S</title>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>section</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A section is a longitudinal part of an edge. When an edge expands from two to three lanes, one section ends (the one with two lanes) and one section starts (the one with three lanes).</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>segment</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A part of an edge (either a lane or a section in dependence on the divisions orientation)</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>street type</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A definition of the attributes of a set of edges (streets). Includes the maximum speed allowed, the number of lanes and the priority of streets that belong to this type. Normally, a single street (edge) can also override any of these vaulues.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>source</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A vehicle emitter.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>source-tar-ball</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A file containing the source for a project - text files containing the program - which must be compiled ("build" to get a runnable application. It is called a "tar-ball" because of the program "tar" which is used to store all files (and subfolders) into a single file.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>submicroscopic</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>In a submicroscopic traffic simulation, the atomic instances are the devices of a vehicle / person.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>sumo-net(work)</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A network description in XML which contains all data needed to route vehicles, perform the simulation on and to visualise the network.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
  </glossdiv>

  <glossdiv>
	<title>T</title>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>Traffic Light Junction</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A junction where the movement of vehicles is controlled by a traffic light.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>Trip Table / Table List</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A list of distinct trips, each specified by the start point, the end point - both given by using the name of the edge - and an explicite time the trip starts at.</para>
		<para>Within SUMO, a trip may contain other values: initial speed of the vehicle, initial lane, initial position</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>type</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>Here: street type</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm >type-file</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>A file containing xml-description of a network's street types.</para>
		<para>Optional input to sumo-netconvert. Is meant to be used in conjunction with an edge-file where edges refer to the previously read types via their name (id).</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
  </glossdiv>

  <glossdiv>
	<title>X</title>
	<glossentry>
	  <glossterm>XML</glossterm>
	  <glossdef>
		<para>"XML (eXtensible Markup Language) is a is the universal format for structured documents and data..." as the w3c says. Further information may be found at <ulink url="http://www.w3c.org/XML/">http://www.w3c.org/XML/</ulink>. All data read by the simulation and written by our tools use this format.</para>
	  </glossdef>
	</glossentry>
  </glossdiv>

</glossary>
